// FAQ
var faqs = [
  {q:"What is the difference between margin and markup?",a:"Margin is profit as a percentage of selling price \u2014 a $100 item with $40 cost has a 60% margin. Markup is profit as a percentage of cost \u2014 the same item has a 150% markup ($60 profit \u00f7 $40 cost). Margin is always lower than markup for the same transaction. The relationship: Margin = Markup \u00f7 (1 + Markup) and Markup = Margin \u00f7 (1 \u2212 Margin)."},
  {q:"How do you calculate gross profit margin?",a:"Gross profit margin = (Revenue \u2212 Cost of Goods Sold) \u00f7 Revenue \u00d7 100. For example, selling a product for $80 that costs $30 to make gives a gross profit of $50 and a gross margin of 62.5%. Gross margin only accounts for direct production costs, not overhead like rent or marketing."},
  {q:"What is a good profit margin for a business?",a:"Good profit margins vary dramatically by industry. SaaS companies achieve 70-85% gross margins. Retail averages 25-50%. Restaurants operate on 60-70% gross (3-9% net). Manufacturing ranges 25-40%. Generally, gross margins above 50% are strong, 30-50% is average, and below 30% is thin. Net profit margins of 10-20% are excellent for most industries."},
  {q:"How do I convert between margin and markup?",a:"Markup to margin: Margin = Markup \u00f7 (1 + Markup). Example: 50% markup \u2192 0.50 \u00f7 1.50 = 33.3% margin. Margin to markup: Markup = Margin \u00f7 (1 \u2212 Margin). Example: 40% margin \u2192 0.40 \u00f7 0.60 = 66.7% markup. Key equivalents: 100% markup = 50% margin, 50% markup = 33.3% margin, 33.3% markup = 25% margin."},
  {q:"What is the difference between gross margin and net margin?",a:"Gross margin subtracts only direct costs (COGS) from revenue. Net margin subtracts all expenses \u2014 COGS, operating expenses, interest, taxes, and depreciation. A company might have 60% gross margin but only 10% net margin after overhead. Gross margin shows production efficiency; net margin shows overall profitability."},
  {q:"How do I calculate selling price from cost and desired margin?",a:"Selling Price = Cost \u00f7 (1 \u2212 Margin). Example: $40 cost with 60% desired margin \u2192 $40 \u00f7 0.40 = $100. A common mistake is adding the margin to cost \u2014 that gives markup pricing, not margin pricing. Adding 60% to $40 gives $64, which is only a 37.5% margin."},
  {q:"How do discounts affect profit margin?",a:"Discounts have a disproportionately large impact. A $100 item with $60 cost has 40% margin and $40 profit. A 10% discount drops profit to $30 \u2014 a 25% reduction, not 10%. At 20% discount, profit falls 50%. To maintain profit after a 10% discount at 40% margin, you need 33% more unit sales."},
  {q:"What markup percentage should I use for my business?",a:"Markup varies by industry: clothing 100-300%, grocery 5-25%, restaurants 200-400% (food), electronics 10-30%, jewelry 100-300%, professional services 100-200%. The right markup depends on overhead costs, competition, and target margin. Start with your desired net margin and work backward."}
];

